College of Medicine. He did his residency at

35
00:02:09.081 --> 00:02:11.060
Brigham and Women's Hospital and fellowship

36
00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:13.800
in medical oncology at Dana-Farber.

37
00:02:15.840 --> 00:02:19.410
He has a very long and distinguished

38
00:02:19.920 --> 00:02:21.000
publication record,

39
00:02:21.980 --> 00:02:24.460
and is currently focusing on

40
00:02:25.340 --> 00:02:29.220
research into CRISPR-Cas9 to understand the mechanisms

41
00:02:29.320 --> 00:02:33.240
that regulate lineage transcription, identity, and novel

42
00:02:33.300 --> 00:02:36.200
targeted therapeutics for small cell lung cancer.

43
00:02:42.900 --> 00:02:46.440
Okay. Well, thank you so much to the organizers and the

44
00:02:46.500 --> 00:02:50.380
invitation to speak, Dr. Byers. So I'm going to talk to you today

45
00:02:50.480 --> 00:02:50.920
about

46
00:02:52.660 --> 00:02:55.730
overall interest in our lab related to regulation and therapeutic

47
00:02:55.820 --> 00:02:59.640
vulnerabilities of small cell lung cancer transcription

48
00:02:59.680 --> 00:03:03.540
factors. Here's my disclosures. So this session's about small cell

49
00:03:03.580 --> 00:03:07.500
lung cancer that accounts for approximately 13% of lung

50
00:03:07.540 --> 00:03:11.340
cancers, and genomically, it's characterized by

51
00:03:11.420 --> 00:03:15.260
near universal loss of function mutations in RB and

52
00:03:15.360 --> 00:03:18.980
P53. And in contrast to non-small cell lung

53
00:03:19.060 --> 00:03:22.960
cancer, small cell lung cancer lacks recurrently mutated

54
00:03:23.000 --> 00:03:24.220
oncogenic drivers.

55
00:03:25.940 --> 00:03:29.210
So over the past several years, through many

56
00:03:30.140 --> 00:03:33.670
groups in the field, it's been appreciated that there are,

57
00:03:34.180 --> 00:03:36.660
although genomically more homogeneous,

58
00:03:37.380 --> 00:03:41.180
epigenetically or transcriptionally, small cell lung cancer is

59
00:03:41.200 --> 00:03:44.560
characterized by these lineage transcription factor subtypes.

60
00:03:44.620 --> 00:03:48.120
So you can think of this broadly as neuroendocrine

61
00:03:48.160 --> 00:03:51.850
subtypes, which make up about 80% of small cell lung cancer, and

62
00:03:51.920 --> 00:03:55.640
non-neuroendocrine subtypes. And within these neuroendocrine subtypes, they're

63
00:03:55.700 --> 00:03:59.260
marked either by ASCL1 dominantly or

64
00:03:59.340 --> 00:04:02.900
neuroD1, and then the non-neuroendocrine subtypes are marked by

65
00:04:02.920 --> 00:04:05.100
Pou2f3 or a triple-negative subtype.

66
00:04:05.580 --> 00:04:09.380
So this has led to a framework to provide personalized

67
00:04:09.440 --> 00:04:13.400
targeted therapeutic strategies, and I think several groups in the field have

68
00:04:13.440 --> 00:04:16.430
identified subtype-specific vulnerabilities.

69
00:04:17.000 --> 00:04:20.880
And so we've been interested really in that these transcription

70
00:04:20.921 --> 00:04:24.580
factors themselves are dependencies in the small cells that

71
00:04:24.620 --> 00:04:28.520
express them. And so we've been doing CRISPR screening to understand

72
00:04:28.560 --> 00:04:31.790
the activity and the regulation of these transcription factors.

73
00:04:31.840 --> 00:04:35.820
I'm not going to go into these projects today, but I'd encourage you to check

74
00:04:35.880 --> 00:04:38.180
out this publication below on Pou2f3.

75
00:04:39.400 --> 00:04:43.160
And so although these transcription factor subtypes are dominantly

76
00:04:44.220 --> 00:04:47.740
expressed and driven by one of the transcription factors, it's been

77
00:04:47.800 --> 00:04:51.790
appreciated that there's intratumoral heterogeneity, and this is

78
00:04:51.800 --> 00:04:55.220
particularly true for ASCL1 and

79
00:04:55.240 --> 00:04:58.580
neuroD1, where about a third of the tumors

80
00:04:58.620 --> 00:05:02.520
express both transcription factors, either in the same cell or in mutually

81
00:05:02.580 --> 00:05:06.420
exclusive cells. And then studies from a couple

82
00:05:06.460 --> 00:05:09.690
different groups, Trudy Oliver's lab, then my lab, found that

83
00:05:10.260 --> 00:05:13.780
genomic alterations in small cell lung cancer can drive

84
00:05:14.160 --> 00:05:17.219
subtype plasticity. So these are just two examples.

85
00:05:17.240 --> 00:05:18.820
This will become important later on.

86
00:05:19.920 --> 00:05:22.900
And so apart from these subtypes

87
00:05:23.880 --> 00:05:27.040
having dependencies in the transcription factors that express them, these

88
00:05:27.080 --> 00:05:30.760
transcription factor programs actually lead to expression of cell

89
00:05:30.900 --> 00:05:34.680
surface antigens. And this has been a really

90
00:05:34.780 --> 00:05:38.060
huge clinical breakthrough of finding

91
00:05:38.160 --> 00:05:41.630
tumor-selective cell surface targeting strategies. And I think Dr.

92
00:05:41.880 --> 00:05:44.540
Byers in the second talk will talk about this broadly.

93
00:05:45.360 --> 00:05:48.780
And three of the targets are DLL3, CES6, and

94
00:05:48.840 --> 00:05:52.400
B7H3, among others. I'm going to specifically talk about

95
00:05:52.440 --> 00:05:55.840
DLL3 in this talk, and a new story that's actually on

96
00:05:55.900 --> 00:05:59.628
bioRxivAnd so DLL3 is most

97
00:05:59.708 --> 00:06:03.528
highly expressed in the ASCL1 subtype of small cell lung cancer.

98
00:06:04.048 --> 00:06:07.278
And that's really because DLL3 is an ASCL1 target gene.

99
00:06:07.658 --> 00:06:11.448
But it's also expressed at very high levels in the neuro D1 subtype, although a

100
00:06:11.508 --> 00:06:14.428
little bit lower levels than ASCL1.

101
00:06:14.438 --> 00:06:17.988
In the PALCH2-F3 subtype, that non-neuroendocrine subtype either

102
00:06:18.008 --> 00:06:20.818
expresses lower or no expression of

103
00:06:20.828 --> 00:06:24.048
DLL3. And so there's several therapeutics in

104
00:06:24.068 --> 00:06:27.988
development targeting DLL3. The most advanced is this

105
00:06:28.008 --> 00:06:31.888
therapeutic tarlatamab, which is a DLL3 bispecific

106
00:06:31.948 --> 00:06:35.108
T-cell engager. So tarlatamab targets

107
00:06:35.748 --> 00:06:39.737
DLL3, CD3 induces T-cell killing of tumor cells

108
00:06:39.768 --> 00:06:43.508
that express DLL3. And this is what I'd argue is probably

109
00:06:43.948 --> 00:06:47.608
one of the biggest clinical breakthroughs of the past several decades.

110
00:06:47.628 --> 00:06:51.408
This is now approved in the second line, for small cell

111
00:06:51.448 --> 00:06:54.428
lung cancer, with a response rate of 35% to

112
00:06:54.588 --> 00:06:58.228
40% and a duration of response of seven to nine months.

113
00:06:58.248 --> 00:07:01.588
But the biomarkers and mechanisms of response and

114
00:07:01.628 --> 00:07:04.228
resistance are not well understood.

115
00:07:05.208 --> 00:07:08.128
And so we really took a two-pronged approach here to

116
00:07:08.188 --> 00:07:12.148
understand determinants and mechanisms of response and

117
00:07:12.188 --> 00:07:16.168
resistance. And this was a wonderful collaboration with

118
00:07:16.208 --> 00:07:20.028
Matt Friedman's lab and Silven Baca's lab at DFCI, and

119
00:07:20.088 --> 00:07:23.428
really beautifully co-led by two fantastic trainees,

120
00:07:24.008 --> 00:07:27.968
Damien Vasseur, postdoc in Matt's lab, and Shin Saito, a postdoc in

121
00:07:28.008 --> 00:07:31.588
my lab. And so what we did really was use

122
00:07:32.028 --> 00:07:35.608
cell-free ChIP-seq from plasma of

123
00:07:35.648 --> 00:07:39.528
patients receiving standard of care tarlatamab prior

124
00:07:39.568 --> 00:07:42.408
to treatment, on treatment, and an acquired resistance,

125
00:07:43.308 --> 00:07:46.888
and in parallel, developed mouse models of

126
00:07:47.208 --> 00:07:49.308
tarlatamab sensitivity and resistance.

127
00:07:49.368 --> 00:07:53.228
And I'll show you how these findings really converged on some

128
00:07:53.428 --> 00:07:56.388
key, I think, fundamental concepts related to this drug.

129
00:07:57.498 --> 00:08:01.078
And so cell-free ChIP-seq, this is an assay from

130
00:08:01.148 --> 00:08:03.968
plasma developed by Silven Baca and Matt Friedman.

131
00:08:04.528 --> 00:08:08.468
And basically, from one ml of plasma can do cell-free

132
00:08:08.508 --> 00:08:12.468
ChIP-seq on histone marks that really correlate with gene

133
00:08:12.508 --> 00:08:16.448
expression. So this is H3K27 acetylation, H3K4

134
00:08:16.508 --> 00:08:19.748
trimethylation, H3K36 trimethylation.

135
00:08:20.188 --> 00:08:24.058
And small cell lung cancer is really an ideal approach for these liquid biopsies

136
00:08:24.108 --> 00:08:28.068
because it has this high cell-free DNA tumor fraction, very

137
00:08:28.128 --> 00:08:31.788
challenging to biopsy, and it's really driven, as I

138
00:08:31.848 --> 00:08:35.739
mentioned, more epigenetically and transcriptionally and not

139
00:08:35.788 --> 00:08:36.268
as much

140
00:08:37.188 --> 00:08:39.808
heterogeneity with the mutations.

141
00:08:39.908 --> 00:08:43.588
So from this cohort that I'm going to talk about, we had 46

142
00:08:43.629 --> 00:08:47.278
patients receiving standard of care tarlatamab, 22 had

143
00:08:47.288 --> 00:08:50.568
clinical benefit, 18 had no clinical benefit.

144
00:08:50.608 --> 00:08:52.288
This is by radiographic response.

145
00:08:52.328 --> 00:08:55.917
So this is in line with response rates seen in larger trials.

146
00:08:57.428 --> 00:09:01.148
And so although these histone marks correlate with gene expression, we

147
00:09:01.188 --> 00:09:04.968
really wanted to be able to more predict gene expression

148
00:09:05.068 --> 00:09:08.688
from plasma. And fortuitously, Goong Galati, who

149
00:09:08.748 --> 00:09:12.548
is a postdoc in Matt Friedman's lab, developed this approach

150
00:09:13.068 --> 00:09:16.468
really by aggregating these histone marks from plasma

151
00:09:17.068 --> 00:09:20.908
and really matching it to the ground truth of RNA-seq

152
00:09:20.928 --> 00:09:23.468
in tumors. And he developed this approach called APEX.

153
00:09:23.588 --> 00:09:26.908
I'm not going to go into detail about it, but you can read about it in this

154
00:09:26.948 --> 00:09:30.408
preprint. In this, he could really correlate single gene

155
00:09:30.468 --> 00:09:34.288
expression at a Spearman correlation of 0.8.

156
00:09:34.368 --> 00:09:38.208
So this is pretty good for inferred RNA-like expression.

157
00:09:38.928 --> 00:09:40.808
And so we applied this to our cohort.

158
00:09:41.628 --> 00:09:45.248
And basically on the right is patients with clinical benefit, on the

159
00:09:45.288 --> 00:09:47.528
left, patients with no clinical benefit.

160
00:09:47.928 --> 00:09:51.588
And just as a sanity check, we are excited to see DLL3.

161
00:09:51.668 --> 00:09:53.748
So this is genome-wide analysis.

162
00:09:54.688 --> 00:09:58.668
But more broadly, what we found is this was the signatures

163
00:09:58.708 --> 00:10:02.688
associated with response were related to many different genes expressed

164
00:10:02.708 --> 00:10:06.428
in the ASCL1 subtype. So this to us suggested that it's actually the

165
00:10:06.548 --> 00:10:10.448
subtype that's correlated with the response, not just DLL3.

166
00:10:11.748 --> 00:10:15.308
So then we did a subtype analysis from the cell-free ChIP-seq

167
00:10:16.268 --> 00:10:20.108
data using APEX, and this is consistent with the APEX results,

168
00:10:20.528 --> 00:10:23.578
sort of at the single gene level. We assigned subtypes,

169
00:10:24.708 --> 00:10:28.448
and the proportions of subtypes are roughly proportional to what we've

170
00:10:28.528 --> 00:10:32.248
seen in patients. And what we found is that really the

171
00:10:32.288 --> 00:10:35.288
ASCL1 subtype highly correlated with the response.

172
00:10:35.408 --> 00:10:37.748
80% of patients with the subtype responded.

173
00:10:38.428 --> 00:10:41.168
None of the PALCH2-F3 patients, although low numbers,

174
00:10:42.268 --> 00:10:44.948
responded, and this was sort of in line with low DLL3.

175
00:10:45.008 --> 00:10:48.488
But I think what was surprising is that neuro D1 subtype,

176
00:10:48.588 --> 00:10:52.458
despite having high levels of DLL3, you can see an example here,

177
00:10:52.528 --> 00:10:56.128
high DLL3 neuro D1 really had very poor

178
00:10:56.148 --> 00:10:59.788
responses, and this will make a little more sense later on.

179
00:11:00.108 --> 00:11:01.708
So now we turn to the mouse, and we

180
00:11:02.848 --> 00:11:06.268
made a syngeneic mouse model to study tarlatamab.

181
00:11:06.308 --> 00:11:10.168
I'm not going to go into a lot of details about the GEM model, but just to say

182
00:11:10.228 --> 00:11:14.127
that from a BLK6 genetically engineered mouse model, we could

183
00:11:14.228 --> 00:11:18.168
isolate tumors and build a syngeneic model that could go back into

184
00:11:18.188 --> 00:11:21.928
BLK6 mice. And what's important to know is that this is an

185
00:11:21.968 --> 00:11:25.378
ASCL1 subtype model. Doesn't express other

186
00:11:25.408 --> 00:11:29.238
transcription factors. And so we could first show that this expresses

187
00:11:29.268 --> 00:11:33.038
DLL3, but importantly, that tarlatamab recognizes

188
00:11:33.088 --> 00:11:36.928
this mouse DLL3, and we could knock out DLL3 and

189
00:11:37.028 --> 00:11:38.808
abrogate the tarlatamab binding.

190
00:11:39.648 --> 00:11:41.428
And we could perform co-culture assays.

191
00:11:41.488 --> 00:11:45.288
Now, this is with human T-cells that basically in the presence of

192
00:11:45.308 --> 00:11:49.188
tarlatamab, you induce a dose-dependent cell killing,

193
00:11:49.268 --> 00:11:52.568
and this was abrogated again by CRISPR inactivation of

194
00:11:52.608 --> 00:11:53.308
DLL3.

195
00:11:54.288 --> 00:11:55.208
But in contrast to

196
00:11:56.128 --> 00:12:00.028
tarlatamab binding mouse DLL3, it does not bind mouse

197
00:12:00.228 --> 00:12:03.688
CD3, and so we had to use a BLK6 transgenic

198
00:12:03.848 --> 00:12:05.204
miceThat where our

199
00:12:06.324 --> 00:12:10.304
company replaced mouse CD3 with human CD3.

200
00:12:11.004 --> 00:12:13.564
So then we ran this through efficacy studies.

201
00:12:13.584 --> 00:12:17.004
And so we basically injected subcutaneous tumors

202
00:12:17.404 --> 00:12:21.254
treated with tarlatamab, and this model has an exquisite response,

203
00:12:21.364 --> 00:12:24.504
really all the mice from the initial cohort had a complete

204
00:12:24.564 --> 00:12:28.294
response, really with three doses out to 160 days.

205
00:12:29.084 --> 00:12:33.064
And this was on target because we saw nothing in black six mice

206
00:12:33.104 --> 00:12:36.924
with mouse CD3, an unrelated bispecific T-cell

207
00:12:36.984 --> 00:12:39.624
engager, BCMA BiTE that

208
00:12:39.684 --> 00:12:43.404
doesn't bind the antigen, but binds human

209
00:12:43.444 --> 00:12:46.944
CD3, did not respond. And remarkably, we could treat

210
00:12:47.064 --> 00:12:50.844
mice really at their endpoint with tarlatamab in tumors that are over

211
00:12:50.884 --> 00:12:54.004
two centimeters and get these complete responses.

212
00:12:54.864 --> 00:12:58.454
And so, thus far, our data suggests in human and

213
00:12:58.524 --> 00:13:02.173
mouse that the ASCL1 subtype is correlated with

214
00:13:02.204 --> 00:13:05.764
response to tarlatamab. So then what happens at acquired resistance?

215
00:13:06.124 --> 00:13:08.584
And so now we turn back to the patients.

216
00:13:08.644 --> 00:13:12.024
And so some of the patients started to develop acquired resistance.

217
00:13:12.084 --> 00:13:15.304
You can see this patient where the tumor fraction increased and

218
00:13:15.344 --> 00:13:19.064
radiographically confirmed a acquired resistance at a little

219
00:13:19.144 --> 00:13:22.844
over 7.5 months. And then we applied APEX really in the

220
00:13:22.884 --> 00:13:26.544
same patient at acquired resistance versus

221
00:13:26.684 --> 00:13:30.624
baseline. And what we saw remarkably was that at

222
00:13:30.664 --> 00:13:34.344
acquired resistance, at baseline, if you compare on the right

223
00:13:34.444 --> 00:13:38.144
side, the genes associated with the ASCL1 subtype went

224
00:13:38.204 --> 00:13:42.124
down, so DLL3 went down. But interestingly, if

225
00:13:42.164 --> 00:13:45.504
you look on the left, so this is what goes up at acquired resistance,

226
00:13:46.204 --> 00:13:49.424
it was many genes associated with the neurod1 subtype.

227
00:13:49.764 --> 00:13:53.464
And so this suggested an ASCL1 to neurod1

228
00:13:53.564 --> 00:13:56.684
subtype selection. You could actually see this at the single gene

229
00:13:56.744 --> 00:14:00.204
locus of neurod1 turning on, DLL3 turning

230
00:14:00.284 --> 00:14:02.684
off and related to subtype signatures.

231
00:14:03.444 --> 00:14:06.944
And so then we had another patient, this is just another vignette, you can read

232
00:14:06.964 --> 00:14:10.744
about other examples in the preprint, that developed an isolated

233
00:14:10.804 --> 00:14:11.484
adrenal

234
00:14:12.424 --> 00:14:16.044
MED that was resected. And really the plasma before it was

235
00:14:16.064 --> 00:14:19.204
resected showed retained DLL3, so high

236
00:14:19.264 --> 00:14:23.164
ASCL1, high DLL3, and that was confirmed by IHC.

237
00:14:24.104 --> 00:14:28.084
But then when we looked at the adrenalectomy, so now this is on tissue, we

238
00:14:28.104 --> 00:14:31.904
were surprised to see that the bulk of cells were T-cells, and

239
00:14:31.944 --> 00:14:35.573
these expressed markers of exhaustion and

240
00:14:35.664 --> 00:14:39.044
markers of regulatory T-cells with FoxP3.

241
00:14:39.164 --> 00:14:41.804
So this was a setting of retained DLL3

242
00:14:41.984 --> 00:14:45.314
suggestive of a defective T-cell response.

243
00:14:46.174 --> 00:14:49.524
So now we'll go back to mouse, and we found some of the same findings.

244
00:14:49.584 --> 00:14:53.504
So we basically treated mice continuously with tarlatamab,

245
00:14:54.084 --> 00:14:58.024
and although they had initial response, occasional mice

